{"type":"message","id":"14119911","parentId":"0a57f17d","timestamp":"2026-04-14T00:36:08.904Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent! Now I have the key data:\n\n**Nasdaq Composite on 4/13/2026:**\n- Close: 23,183.74\n- Change: +276.95 (0.00%... that's strange, the change seems to show 0% which might be an error)\n\nWait, the \"0.00%\" might mean the data is from the day's close and hasn't changed from the previous close displayed, or it means today vs previous day is 0%. Actually, looking at the data:\n- \"Previous Close\" also shows 23,183.74\n- This suggests the Nasdaq closed at 23,183.74 on 4/13\n\nCompared to 4/10 close of 22,902.89:\n\n\n- Change from 4/10 to 4/13: 23,183.74 - 22,902.89 = +280.85 points, or about +1.23%\n\nBut wait, the data shows \"Today’s High\" as 23,187.96 and \"Today’s Low\" as 22,795.82, so there was intraday movement. The 0.00% change displayed might be a data display issue since \"Previous Close\" and the current close are both showing 23,183.74.\n\nThe Nasdaq close on 4/13 was 23,183.74, up from 22,902.89 on 4/10 — that's roughly a +1.2% gain across those three days. The 0.00% change display seems like an artifact of the data format. I should verify this with the Philadelphia Stock Exchange index as well to get a complete picture of the broader market movement during that period. I'm noticing a discrepancy between the two sources—the first shows SOX closing at 9039.5 with a +1.68% change on April 13, while the second shows it at 8949.8 with only a +0.67% gain. This could indicate they might be pulling different trading sessions or there's been some data reconciliation happening. I should verify the SOX data against the first source to resolve the inconsistency, then use the confirmed Nasdaq figure to revise the morning prediction with the accurate April 13 closing values. I'm weighing whether the bullish case strengthens or weakens with the new market data. The Nasdaq's continued strength and new all-time high are clearly positive signals, which actually reinforce the bullish thesis and raise my probability estimates slightly. However, I need to be careful not to overweight this single data point—the SOX data is less reliable, so I should focus primarily on the Nasdaq confirmation of the uptrend.","thinkingSignature":"8970ea8b1cad766936f45602ff4da6ebb334ffe8e77bd8197ed08dd2d150de44"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ygmtclh4t3x6_1","name":"web_fetch","arguments":{"url":"https://www.wantgoo.com/global/sox","extractMode":"text","maxChars":3000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":20070,"output":599,"cacheRead":18540,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39209,"cost":{"input":0.0060209999999999994,"output":0.0007188,"cacheRead":0.0011124,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0078522}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776126949562,"responseId":"062cbee5e09b8bea865cda9f7cf03fb3"}}
