{"type":"message","id":"649a5aeb","parentId":"4e309e8f","timestamp":"2026-04-14T03:00:07.435Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_7ra3cqgwjz8a_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"          \"edit\",\n          \"apply_patch\",\n          \"sessions_list\",\n          \"sessions_history\",\n          \"sessions_send\",\n          \"sessions_spawn\",\n          \"session_status\",\n        ],\n        deny: [\"browser\", \"canvas\", \"nodes\", \"cron\", \"discord\", \"gateway\"],\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\n<Accordion title=\"Sandbox details\">\n\n**Backend:**\n\n- `docker`: local Docker runtime (default)\n- `ssh`: generic SSH-backed remote runtime\n- `openshell`: OpenShell runtime\n\nWhen `backend: \"openshell\"` is selected, runtime-specific settings move to\n`plugins.entries.openshell.config`.\n\n**SSH backend config:**\n\n- `target`: SSH target in `user@host[:port]` form\n- `command`: SSH client command (default: `ssh`)\n\n[2264 more lines in file. Use offset=1480 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776135607433}}
{"type":"message","id":"5cabff8a","parentId":"649a5aeb","timestamp":"2026-04-14T03:00:19.275Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - this is a `deny` list within a specific binding context, not the global config. Let me now look at what the actual issue is. \n\nThe key problem is that when I try to use `cron add`, it says \"pairing required\". This seems to be a gateway-level authentication issue, not a tool permission issue.\n\nLet me look at the actual gateway configuration to see if there's something related to cron requiring pairing. Let me check the gateway's trust model for internal tools.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The cron tool's `list` and `status` work fine (they read directly from the jobs.json file), but `add` fails. This suggests:\n1. The file read operations are direct file access\n2. The write operations go through the gateway RPC\n\nBut the gateway RPC requires pairing/authentication. Looking at the paired.json, the `gateway-client` only has `operator.read` scope, not `operator.write` scope.\n\nWait - but the `openclaw-control-ui` has `operator.write`. \n\nSo the real issue is that the cron tool's write operations are attempting to use the gateway's RPC interface, which is rejecting the unauthenticated request because it requires pairing credentials. The tool needs either direct file system access for these operations or proper gateway authentication to bypass the pairing requirement. I need to verify the gateway's port configuration and check whether the tool is connecting to the correct endpoint for the cron operations.","thinkingSignature":"cfb28e99bcb93ef85af8e0993ca2d4f4ab82eec368369de898a2acc22d8dce1a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i4tuak6kzll6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X POST \"http://127.0.0.1:18789/\" -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" -d '{\"method\":\"cron.list\",\"params\":{}}' 2>&1 | head -5"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i4tuak6kzll6_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X POST \"http://127.0.0.1:18789/cron\" -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" -d '{\"method\":\"cron.list\",\"params\":{}}' 2>&1 | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":40629,"output":443,"cacheRead":18540,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59612,"cost":{"input":0.0121887,"output":0.0005316,"cacheRead":0.0011124,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0138327}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776135607440,"responseId":"062ce0b7f759f3b33c2617a59c8c2b38"}}
